  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Mandates reporting of certain transactions\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased government's ability to track financial transactions\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering laws\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define various money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nThese statutes apply to financial institutions, businesses, and individuals, requiring them to implement compliance programs and report suspicious financial activities to prevent and detect money laundering.",
